<h3 class="customheader">Spices &amp; Herbs</h3>
<div>
    <p>
        Spices constitute important group of agricultural commodities which are virtually indispensable in the culinary art.
    </p>
    <p>
        They can primarily defined as farm products used in various forms, like-fresh ripe, dried, broken, powdered, etc. Which contributes aroma, taste, flavor, colour and pungency to food, rather than a lone food seasoning factor. Spices may be bark, buds, flowers, fruits, leaves, rhizomes, root, seeds, stigmas and styles or the entire plant tops.
    </p>
    <p>
        They can be appetizers or preservatives and many of them have rich medicinal properties and are used in pharmaceutical, perfumery, cosmetic products etc.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>BLACK PEPPER</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Piper nigrum)</b><br />
    <b>Locally known as ‘Mirin’ or ‘Kale Miri’</b>
    <p>
        It is a creeper which grows very much like a phyladendron with aerial roots emerging at the nodal joints which prefer to grip a rough bark of a tree as it climbs (and is definitely not a parasite) it produces berries in December and January which when dried yields pepper of commerce.
    </p>
    <p>
        In Ayurvedic traditions black pepper or marich (Mire) is named after the Sanskrit word for the sun. Black pepper contains very potent solar energy and is a powerful digestive stimulant. Black pepper is rajastic or energy producing in nature. Black pepper stimulates the plasma and the blood, the nervous system & the spleen, reduces fat and can stimulate the circulation to help warm, cold hands and feet. It is a very good antiseptic for internal digestive organs the oils can be used to clear sinus congestion.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>CINNAMON</h4>
    <b>(BOTANICAL name: Cinnamon Zeylanicum)</b><br />
    <b>Locally known as ‘Tikhi’</b>
    <p>
        Dried pieces of inner bark of branches is Cinnamon which is of economic importance. Leaves are also used as spices. Select cinnamon seedlings of good origin or use grafts of good varieties. Cinnamon grows well in sunny open areas with protective irrigation. It can also be grown as an intercrop in coconut gardens.
    </p>
    <p>
        Ancient ayurvedic practitioners used it as a treatment for fevers, diarrhea and to mask unpleasant flavor in other healing herbs. It is a pungent, sweet astringent with stimulating healing qualities. Cinnamon is recommended for respiratory ailments such as colds, sinus congestion and bronchitis. As a digestive aid, it relieves dyspepsia, intestinal infection and parasites.: It aids circulation and helps to alienate anaemia. Cinnamon is useful for the treatment of scabies and lice,
        because of its strong antibacterial effect cinnamon can be used to treat minor scrapes and cuts, first wash these cuts and than apply powdered cinnamon. Cinnamon stimulates a sluggish digestion it. Helps to fortify the immune system against chills and infections, it can really mental fatigue, improves poor concentration and nervous exhaustion and helps to lift depression, sprinkle a few drops on rolled cinnamon sticks and add to pot pourri made from
        dried orange peal or orange oil and basil for a room freshener that stimulates and refreshes the mind, relieves tension and soothes the nerves.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>CLOVES</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Engenia Caryophyllus)</b><br />
    <b>Locally known as : Lavang</b>
    <p>
        Dry unopened flower bud of the clove is used as a spice. Clove is a medium size evergreen tree which grows in semi-shade conditions.The plant flowers after about 5 years. The flower bud just before opening is picked and dried in shade. The clove loses its value if the bud is allowed to open. One tree gives about 200-500 gm of dry cloves annually.
        It is a bud of a tropical ever green tree, now common as a kitchen spice.

    </p>
    <p>
        Its sweetening deodorizing properties have long been used externally in potpourris, incense and air fresheners, clove can also be used as an internal deodorizer, freshening the breath and reducing body odour (Odour). As an antiseptic it has been used in treating toothache. Clove tones muscles and expectant mothers are recommended to eat cloves in the last month of pregnancy to strengthen the uterus. Clove has long been used to flight bacteria, tooth decay and anaesthetize dental pain.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>NUTMEG</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Myristica Franganse)</b><br />
    <b>Locally known as: Jaifal</b>
    <p>
        The dry seed is called Nutmeg and the outer arid of the nutmeg is called mace (Jaipatri) both are the products of the same tree. This seed is taken out of the ripe nutmeg fruit and the outer arid is skillful separated. Both are dried in shade. A graft or seedlings may yield between 50 – 500 nutmeg fruits per year. Each fruit yields about 1 gm of mace. Fruit is harvested when fully ripe. Yellow and just about to split open.
    </p>
    <p>
        It a tropical evergreen tree, native to Indonesia. The brown wrinkled fruit contains a kernel which is covered by a bright red membrane which produces a spice called mace. Nutmeg improves appetite and digestion, nutmeg is highly toxic when ingested in large doses and is only recommended for use in small doses of 1 teaspoon or less; nutmeg is calming and sleep inducing, making it an excellent remedy for insomnia and other sleep disorders. It has been used to treat diarrhoea and vomiting. In small quantities it acts on the stomach improving digestion and appetite, while dispelling flatulence or acid stomach.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>CARDAMON</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Elletaria Cardamomum)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Velchi, Yel</b>
    <p>
        Among the spices of India, Cardamom occupies a pre-eminent position, perhaps only next to black pepper. Itbelongs to ginga group. The plant gives long floral stalks in March to May which bear the capsules which when dried yield cardamom. The floral stalks grow on the ground to a length of 1 to 2 feet and look more like aerial roots. The plant is shade loving and prefers humid cool areas for growth.
    </p>
    <p>
        Is particularly good for opening the flow of vital energy through the body. Added to milk cardamom will neutralize mucus – forming properties. Added to coffeeit detoxifies caffeine , it aids in the digestion of fats and starches, stimulates the spleen and calms acid stomach and acid regurgitation. Cardamom suppresses vomiting when eaten with a banana. Cardamom also has a wonderful stimulating and tonic effect on mind and body. It makes it refreshing both which can relieve fatigue and soothe strained narves massage oil for stomach cramps, add 1 drop 2 teaspoons (long) veg. oil and massage in a clockwise on stomach etc.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>CORIANDER</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Coriandrum Sativum Elletaria Cardamomum)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Kotmir</b>
    <p>
        Coriander is one of the commonest ingredients used in cooking both in the form of seeds, and live plant. (In the cooked form or raw on salads). Sprouted coriander seeds are grown in patches of pre-prepard alluvial soil at the end of the monsoon season i.e August / September. The plant takes one to one and half month to mature and in harvested like spinage for cooking. If plants is allowed further growth it Faeroes producing, seeds which is used as spice. Originated in India, the herbs was said to ‘stimulate arousal and confer immortality’. A popular ingredient in curry, spice blends.
    </p>
    <p>
        Coriander alleviates urinary infection, cystitis, rashes, burns digestive disorders such as gas pains vomiting and indigestion. It purifies the blood, decongests the liver and reduces heat and fever in the body. As a anti-inflammatory coriander benefits arthritis. For colic, coriander’s pain relieving properties make it suitable for headaches and neuralgia. It has a warming ant-rheumatic effect, good for muscular pains and stiffness, arthritis and rheumatism, coriander muscle rub.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>CUMIN</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Cuminum Cyminum)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Jeera</b>
    <p>
        It is believed in Ayurveda that cumin has a cooling effect on the human body and therefore it has a definitive role particularly in warm seasons and climates. Cumin seedsare pungent and savoury brown seeds, cumin is very rich in vitamins and minerals and is an antidote to weakness and fatigue. It acts as a blood cleanser, a carminative, aiding in the absorption of nutrients in the system; used for treatment of digestive disorders and gas, pains,
        anemia, migraine, allergies, nervous conditions, low break milk and lack of sexual drive. Cumin builds up the immune system of people who suffer severe allergies. To relieve abdominal pain, add the seeds to with a cumin seed poultice first soak 2 table spoons of cumin seeds in hot water for 2 hours, strain, dry, then crush the seeds, add serval drops of peppermint oil, a little flour and some hot water to make a paste. Mix well spread this mixture on muslin or the cloth and apply over the abdomen to relieve liver, stomach and gall bladder pains.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>MUSTARD</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: (Brassica Nigra)</b><br />
    <b>Locally knowns as (Sasuwa)</b>
    <p>
        Mustard seeds are first and then grown in pre prepared patches of alluvial soil consisting of a good dose of organic manure. The spouted seed are then grown the mustard plant grows to a height of 2 feet on maturity the yields flowers from which elongated pods grow yielding mustard seeds inside. The useful irritant mustard, which is an irritant, has also proved medicinally useful.
    </p>
    <p>
        There are three distinct species of mustard black white and brown. All three exhibit almost the same irritant properties. It is this quality which encourages blood flow towards the surface in cases of rheumatism, sciatica, peritonitis, neuralgia and various internal inflammations. Taken internally in small amounts as is being done in our daily coking (in tempering), it increases the appetite and stimulates the production of gastric juices.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>CHILLI </h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Capsicum frutescens)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Mirisang</b>
    <p>
        What imparts the so-called “Indianness” to the cuisine of the subcontinent is that green, slender fruit called chilli. Some four hundred years ago Indians were not familiar with chillies at all the fruit which looked like the tail of a scorpion and tasted like its sting. It was the Portuguese who brought chillies along with their cannons to India. Fruit of the sun Chilli ismetaphorically referred to in Sanskrit as Marichi-Palam, the sun’s fruit. Like black pepper (marich), chilli is also believed to be as hot as the sun.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>GINGER </h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Zingiber Officinale)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Alle</b>
    <p>
        Is a rhizome that grows under the ground. It is used both raw and dried. The raw variety is also know a vegetable ginger. The dried variety is sun dried for a week and then ached with lime. Is a native to India, where the ancient Ayurvedic used it to preserve food as a digestive aid and asa spiritual and physical cleanser. It is a pungent sweet herbs, a stimulant and expectorant it stimulates all tissues of the body and is recommended in cases where the illness is due to poor assimilation.
    </p>
    <p>
        For motion sickness (on land sea or in the air) use a few drops of ginger oil on a small bandage and place it behind the ear or take ginger tablets or make ginger tea with 2 teaspoons of the grated root to 1 cup of boiling water, let it steep for 5 minutes and then drink. Massaged around the stomach and abdomen diluted ginger calms the digestion, valuable for preventing and treating colds, sore throats it also eases coughing and since it bring sweat, good for flu. Word of caution the outer rind of both fresh as well as dried ginger needs to be discarded before use.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>TURMERIC </h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Curcuma Longa)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: halddi</b>
    <p>
        Is a rhizome like ginger. It is normally used in powdered form. It is a perennial herb. It has short stem and raised of lifted branches, the underground stem or rhizome are short and thick and constitute commercial turmeric. It is prepared by boiling of rhizomes in water and then drying and powdering them.
    </p>
    <p>
        Besides flavour, turmeric is a natural dye allopathic drugs too use turmeric for colouring. Holds a place of honour in Ayurvedic medicine. It is asymbol of prosperity and was believed to be a cleanser for all the systems in the body. Turmeric was prescribed as a digestive aid, a treatment for fever, infection, dysentery, arthritis, jaundice and it has been used as basic ingredient in curries for thousands of years. Reduces fat, purifies blood and aids circulation.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>ONION </h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Allium Cepa)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Piaoe</b>
    <p>
        Onion and its relative garlic are members of the lily family. They are some of the oldest known medicinal plants, rich in trace elements, minerals and sulphur. Ayurvedic practitioners prescribed onion for cancer and leprosy. Onion stimulates the production of saliva and digestive juices, as well as the flow of tears. Onion is a pungent sweet bulb with heating and drying qualities, it is a carminative and expectorant, onion has a rejuvenating effect on all tissues and body systems.
        Onion helps eliminate lead and other heavy metals from the body and is beneficial for diabetes. Onion juice has been used to treat infected wounds, amoebic dysentery, onion may be used directly on the skin for natural relief from burns.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>GARLIC</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Allium Sativum)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Lusson</b>
    <p>
        Garlic is one of the oldest known medicinal plants. Garlic has been used to treat a broad spectrum of ailments. Its stimulating effect aids in the secretion of digestive juices. Garlic may be used as a natural antibiotic and as a blood pressure and cholesterol reducer. To obtain antibiotic effects, chew 6-12 roasted cloves of garlic a day. Cleanses the blood and helps to create maintain healthy bacteria population (flora) in the gut. Helps to bring down fever, tones the heart and circulatory system.
    </p>
    <p>
        Fresh garlic juice is antifungal and can be applied neat to infections such as athlete’s foot. Chew whole roasted garlic eaten daily can reduce chronic acidity of the stomach. Garlic oil derives its peculiar smell from its sulphur containing volatile oil which accounts for most of its medicinal properties. The oil has an antibiotic action on the gastrointestinal tract. It spreads through out the body and is secreted along with toxic washed, via sweat, urine, faces, etc. The bactericidal effect of garlic oil on typhoid bacilli is found to be twenty four times greater than that of carbolic acid as measured by the most modern methods. Garlic infused oil can be used as a chest rub for a respiratory or digestive ailments or in the ear to reduce inflammation.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>SAFFRON</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Crocus Sativus)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Kessar</b>
    <p>
        Is a small perennial crocus with purple flower cultivated in Spain, France, Sicily, Iran and India. The younger plant does not flower for the first few years, when it matures, it produces flowers with golden stigmas which are highly valued for their medicinal and aphrodisiac properties as well as their delicious flower.
    </p>
    <p>
        Saffron is frequently used as an emmenagogue and expectorant, aids digestion and improves appetite. A saffron infusion can be helpful for irregular menstruation and menstrual pains. Saffron is prized for its aphrodisiac qualities.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>BASIL</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Ocimum Sanctum)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Tulsi</b>
    <p>
        There are different varieties of basil. The Indian variety is also called basil Krishna because it is said that Krishna wore garlands of this herbs around his neck to increase his detachment and his faith. The faithful continue this practice, believing basil to be a protector in life and death.
    </p>
    <p>
        Ayurveda have used basil to treat stomach, kidney and blood aliments. Basil can provide relief for colds, coughs, asthma, sinus congaetion, headaches, arthritis, rheumatism and fever, basil oil kills intestinal parasites and as such is recommended for abdominal conditions and stomachache.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>SANDALWOOD</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Santalum album)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Chandan</b>
    <p>
        Sandalwood has been in use in India right from Vedic times. It was used in a cometic ointment called urguja along with oil of aloe, rose and jasmine. Like tulsi, sandalwood is considered scared by the Hindus. It is traditionally believed that sandalwood helps in opening the third eye. Hence it is often applied on the forehead. It is also believed to aid the transmutation of sexual energy into spiritual energy. Meditators or sadhakas use in the form of agarbathi (inscence stick) as oil or paste or infusion it is believed that its aroma aids in meditation.
    </p>
    <p>
        Sandalwood while the aromatic wood is used to make scented carvings, the medicinal properties are in the oil, which can be pressed from the wood or extracted with alcohol or water. Sandalwood has been used to treat cyclitis, urethritis, vaginitis, acute dermatitis, herpes, bronchitis, palpitations, gonorrhoea, sunstroke, dry skin, acne, nausea, tuberculosis. Sandalwood can cure skin problem that are bacterial in origin. (Sandalwood is an antiseptic effective for all urinary disorders). It is a trusted insect repellent. Sandalwood oil soothers the stomach and reduce digestive sporms, it encourages would healing. Sandalwood oil, along with rose oil, is widely used in aroma therapy.
    </p>
</div>
<div>
    <h4>NEEM</h4>
    <b>(Botanical name: Azadirachia Indica)</b><br />
    <b>Locally know as: Kudu Limbdo</b>
    <p>
        In this otherwise pollution-wrapped planet, it is heartening to note that over eighteen million neem trees, dedicated air-purifiers, are constantly engaged in releasing pure oxygen into the air, replacing toxic carbon gases. Almost all parts of this tree can claim some or the other medicinal use. For the Hindus, it has a certain spiritual significance too. It is believed that its abundant inflorescences promote spiritual achievements.
    </p>
</div>
